</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Revenues
	from the Systems segment for 2015 were &euro;11.1&nbsp;million, up 22.7% over 2014. The total number of units sold rose 28.6% to eighteen in 2015 in comparison to
	fourteen in 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	average, the 3D printers sold in 2015 were larger systems (
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	i.e.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, VX1000) than in prior years, which also contributed to higher revenues
	as the larger systems are generally sold at higher prices. Revenues depend not only on the number of units sold, but also on the composition of the units sold, with new, larger, higher-performance
	printers generating higher revenues per unit.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Revenues
	from the Services segment for 2015 were &euro;13.0&nbsp;million, which represents an increase of &euro;5.8&nbsp;million or 82.3% over revenues of
	&euro;7.1&nbsp;million in 2014. The increase in Services revenues was primarily due to the inclusion of results from our UK subsidiary, which contributed revenues of
	&euro;4.7&nbsp;million in 2015 compared to &euro;0.9&nbsp;million in 2014, as well as increased capacity at our service center in Germany. The part of the business of
	voxeljet UK disposed of in the course of the restructuring contributed approximately &euro;3.8&nbsp;million to 2015 revenues. Our revenues from the Services segment in 2015 also included
	approximately &euro;0.5&nbsp;million from our U.S. subsidiary, voxeljet America&nbsp;Inc., which began printing on-demand parts in the first quarter of 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	50
</FONT>
</P>

</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	generated most of our revenues in the EMEA but achieved significant growth in the Americas region in 2015. Revenues in the Americas increased as we generated higher revenues from our
	American subsidiary operating in the U.S. market. The revenues in the Asia Pacific region were lower due to lower 3D printer sales in this region.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Gross Profit and Gross Profit Margin
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Total gross profit for 2015 increased by &euro;0.6&nbsp;million, or 9.4%, reflecting higher sales in both our Systems and
	Services segments in 2015 compared to 2014. Our gross profit margin was 28.7% in 2015 compared to 39.1% in 2014, to a significant extent declining as a result of the restructuring of voxeljet UK. In
	addition, personnel expenses increased because of higher headcount to pursue our growth strategy.
</FONT>
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross
	profit for our Systems segment increased to &euro;3.8&nbsp;million in 2015 from &euro;3.3&nbsp;million in 2014, while the gross profit margin of our
	Systems segment decreased by 1.8% to 34.6% in 2015 from 36.4% in 2014. This decrease in gross profit margin resulted primarily from higher cost of sales because of increased personnel expenses
	associated with increased headcount related to the pursuit of our growth strategy. Furthermore it reflected the product mix, as we sold more used and refurbished printers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross
	profit for our Services segment in 2015 amounted to &euro;3.1&nbsp;million, unchanged as compared to 2014. The gross profit margin decreased from 42.6% in 2014 to
	23.7% in 2015. The gross profit margin in this segment was impacted in the amount of &euro;&nbsp;1.4&nbsp;million by the restructuring of the voxeljet UK business which
	contributed 10.6% to the gross margin decline.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	51
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating Expenses
</I>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As shown in the table below, total operating expenses increased by &euro;5.8&nbsp;million to
	&euro;16.3&nbsp;million in 2015 from &euro;10.5&nbsp;million in 2014, and increased to 67.9% of revenues compared to 65.1% in 2014. This increase affected all areas of our
	operations.
</FONT>

</FONT>

<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">

<TD ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	28.8
</FONT>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	increase in selling expenses in 2015 was primarily related to increased support for voxeljet UK as well as the buildup of a sales force for voxeljet America. Furthermore, we
	experienced higher costs related to our sales agents and attended more global exhibitions, which increased travel expenses significantly. As a result, our selling expenses increased at a faster rate
	than our revenues.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	our business grew in 2015, we continued to invest in research and development. Our research and development expenses amounted to 22.7% of our revenues in 2015, reflecting a 35.8%
	increase in our research and development expenses compared to 2014. Until November&nbsp;30, 2015 research and development expenses included salaries for employees of voxeljet UK, who were working in
	this function. Those employees were transferred within the restructuring of voxeljet UK. Research and development is a key element of our strategy to develop new material sets and enhancements to our
	3D printers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	operating expenses are also affected by headcount, which increased to 223 employees in 2015 from 200 employees in 2014, primarily in our Systems segment.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	had an operating loss of &euro;9.4&nbsp;million in 2015, an increase of &euro;5.2&nbsp;million compared to an operating loss of
	&euro;4.2&nbsp;million in 2014. This higher operating loss resulted from the restructuring of our subsidiary voxeljet UK, higher headcount as well as ramp up losses from our U.S.
	subsidiary, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	expect our profitability to improve in the coming years as we continue to achieve economies of scale and can further leverage our fixed expenses. Through the restructuring of our
	subsidiary voxeljet
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	52
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=12,SEQ=54,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=751735,FOLIO='52',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]DK76001A.;25',USER='JLAWRENA',CD='31-MAR-2016;16:43' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DK76001_1_53">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	UK,
	we expect to be able to increase gross margins. Additionally, the restructuring provides a lean and efficient administration of the subsidiary. Further steps towards realizing higher profitability
	include increasing revenues in order to leverage fixed costs like amortization and depreciation and rent expense. Those positive effects will be partially offset by expenses related to the ramp up
	phase of our new subsidiaries in India and China.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Financial Result
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Financial result was a &euro;0.1&nbsp;million and &euro;0.2&nbsp;million expense in 2015 and 2014,
	respectively and consequently shows no significant changes.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Provision for Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income tax expense for 2015 was &euro;0.1&nbsp;million compared to income tax benefit of
	&euro;0.1&nbsp;million in 2014. We did not recognize deferred tax assets for loss carry-forwards as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, which results in income tax expense on a loss before
	taxes.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Taxation of the Company in Germany
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;German stock corporations are subject to a Corporation Tax of 15%. A 5.5% solidarity surcharge is imposed on the Corporation Tax,
	resulting in an overall tax rate of 15.825%. In addition, German stock corporations are by virtue of their legal form subject to a municipal profit-related German Trade Tax. The Trade Tax is
	calculated on the basis of the taxable Corporation Tax income as shown in the annual statutory profit and loss accounts of the stock corporation which, however, is subject to certain particular Trade
	Tax add-backs and deductions. The effective Trade Tax rate applicable depends on the municipality in which the stock corporation maintains a permanent establishment and ranges between approximately 7%
	and 17%. The Corporation Tax and Trade Tax combined will result in an overall tax burden for German stock corporations of approximately 28% on average. The deduction for a taxable loss carry-forward
	for the fiscal year has a limit of &euro;1&nbsp;million; thereafter taxable income can only be offset by up to 60%. The loss carry-forward is reduced by the amount used and has an
	unlimited life. However, there are limitations on the use of loss carry-forwards upon a transfer of more than 25% of a stock corporation's shares or voting rights to a single purchaser, a related
	party or a group of purchasers within a specified time period, and existing loss carry-forwards are completely lost in the case of a transfer of more than 50% of a stock corporation's shares or voting
	rights to any of the aforementioned persons within a period of five years. However, these limitations do not apply to the amount of the tax loss carry-forwards which do not exceed the existing excess
	of fair value over tax basis in the corporation at the time of transfer.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Loss
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2015 we had a loss of approximately &euro;9.6&nbsp;million compared to a loss of &euro;4.3&nbsp;million in
	2014. The &euro;5.3&nbsp;million increase in loss resulted from charges related the restructuring of voxeljet UK, and increased operating expenses resulting from additional personnel
	employed in pursuit of our growth strategy.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	53
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>

<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Summary
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our revenues increased by &euro;4.5&nbsp;million, or 38.3%, to &euro;16.2&nbsp;million in 2014 from
	&euro;11.7&nbsp;million in 2013. Revenues for 2014 increased due to a combination of an increase in the number of 3D printers sold and an increase in our printing of on-demand parts for
	our customers. In 2014 we sold fourteen 3D printers compared to nine 3D printers sold in 2013. Revenues from the printing of on-demand parts for our customers increased 33.0% primarily due to
	increased capacity at our recently expanded service center in Germany as well as the inclusion of results from our UK subsidiary in the fourth quarter of 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	gross profit for 2014 increased by &euro;1.7&nbsp;million, or 36.2%, to &euro;6.3&nbsp;million from &euro;4.6&nbsp;million in 2013. Our higher
	gross profit for 2014 resulted primarily from increased sales of 3D printers in 2014 and the product mix in our Systems segment. Our gross profit margin was 39.1% in 2014 compared to 39.7% in 2013.
	The gross margin in 2014 was impacted by increased cost of sales caused primarily by higher personnel expenses in manufacturing as we increased our headcount to 72 in 2014 from 38 in 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	operating profit declined by &euro;1.5&nbsp;million to a loss of &euro;4.2&nbsp;million in 2014 from a loss of &euro;2.7&nbsp;million in 2013.
	This was due to a higher level of operating expenses in connection with being a public company and with the buildup of personnel resources to pursue our growth strategy. Our headcount in all
	departments increased to 200 in 2014 from 106 in 2013. Additionally, other research and development expenses increased by &euro;1.4&nbsp;million and selling expenses increased by
	&euro;1.1&nbsp;million. This is due to our growth strategy and our efforts to strengthen our technological leadership.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	54
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>

</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Revenues
	from the Systems segment for 2014 were &euro;9.1&nbsp;million, up 42.8% over 2013. The total number of units sold rose 35.7% to fourteen in 2014 in comparison to
	nine in 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	average, the 3D printers sold in 2014 were larger systems (
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	i.e.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, VX1000) than in prior years, which also contributed to higher revenues
	as the larger systems are generally sold at higher prices. Revenues depend not only on the number of units sold, but also on the composition of the units sold, with new, larger, higher-performance
	printers generating higher revenues per unit.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Revenues
	from the Services segment for 2014 were &euro;7.1&nbsp;million, which represents an increase of &euro;1.8&nbsp;million or 32.9% over revenues of
	&euro;5.3&nbsp;million in 2013. The increase in Services revenues was primarily due to increased capacity at our recently expanded service center in Germany as well as the inclusion of
	results from our UK subsidiary in the fourth quarter of 2014, which contributed revenue of &euro;0.9&nbsp;million. Our revenues from the Services segment in 2014 did not include any
	contribution from our U.S. subsidiary, voxeljet America&nbsp;Inc., which began printing on-demand parts in the first quarter of 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	generated most of our revenues in the EMEA but achieved significant growth in the Asia Pacific regions in 2014. Revenues in both the Asia Pacific region and the Americas increased as
	we sold five 3D printers in those two regions in 2014 but none in 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Gross Profit and Gross Profit Margin
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Total gross profit for 2014 increased by &euro;1.7&nbsp;million, or 36.2%, reflecting higher sales in both our Systems and
	Services segments in 2014 compared to 2013. Our gross profit margin was 39.1% in 2014 compared to 39.7% in 2013 primarily as a result of increased cost of sales due to higher personnel expenses
	related to the LTCIP. These LTCIP-related expenses amounted to &euro;0.2&nbsp;million in total, or &euro;0.1&nbsp;million within the Systems segment and
	&euro;0.1&nbsp;million within the Services segment. In addition, personnel expenses increased because of higher headcount to pursue our growth strategy.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	55
</FONT>
</P>

</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross
	profit for our Systems segment increased to &euro;3.3&nbsp;million in 2014 from &euro;2.5&nbsp;million in 2013, while the gross profit margin of our
	Systems segment decreased by 3.1% to 36.4% in 2014 from 39.5% in 2013. This decrease in gross profit margin resulted primarily from higher cost of sales because of increased personnel expenses
	associated with increased headcount related to the pursuit of our growth strategy.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross
	profit for our Services segment increased by &euro;0.9&nbsp;million from 2013 to 2014, while the gross profit margin increased from 40.0% in 2013 to 42.6% in 2014. The
	gross profit margin in this segment was affected by favorable product mix and increased efficiency.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_20"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating Expenses
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As shown in the table below, total operating expenses increased by &euro;3.9&nbsp;million to
	&euro;10.5&nbsp;million in 2014 from &euro;6.7&nbsp;million in 2013, and increased to 65.2% of revenues compared to 56.9% in 2013. This increase affected all areas of our
	operations.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	increase in selling expenses in 2014 was primarily related to increased headcount to support the growth of our business. Furthermore, we experienced higher costs related to our sales
	agents and attended more global exhibitions, which increased travel expenses significantly. As a result, our selling expenses increased at a faster rate than our revenues.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	our business grew in 2014, we continued to invest in research and development. Our research and development expenses amounted to 24.9% of our revenues in 2014, reflecting a 51.9%
	increase in our research and development expenses compared to 2013. Research and development is a key element of our strategy to develop new material sets and enhancements to our 3D printers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	operating expenses are also affected by headcount, which increased to 200 employees in 2014 from 106 employees in 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	56
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	had an operating loss of &euro;4.2&nbsp;million in 2014, an increase of &euro;2.2&nbsp;million compared to an operating loss of
	&euro;2.0&nbsp;million in 2013. This increase resulted primarily from higher headcount related to the pursuit of our growth strategy and the LTCIP, which had a negative impact of
	&euro;0.5&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	expect our profitability to improve in the coming years as we continue to achieve economies of scale and can further leverage our fixed expenses. The first step towards realizing this
	goal was achieved through the purchase of the land and buildings comprising our headquarters in Germany at the end of 2013, which will reduce our rental expenses going forward. The positive effect on
	our operating profit resulting from the decrease in rental expenses will be partially offset by the depreciation that will accumulate on the buildings. In addition, we expect our subsidiaries in the
	U.S. and the UK to contribute positively to our future profitability.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Financial Result
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Financial result was a &euro;0.2&nbsp;million and &euro;0.3&nbsp;million expense in 2014 and 2013,
	respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Provision for Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income tax benefit for 2014 was &euro;0.1&nbsp;million compared to income tax expense of
	&euro;0.4&nbsp;million in 2013. We did not recognize deferred tax assets for loss carry-forwards as of December&nbsp;31, 2014, which results in income tax expense on a loss before
	taxes.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Loss
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2014 we had a loss of approximately &euro;4.2&nbsp;million compared to a loss of &euro;2.7&nbsp;million in
	2013. The &euro;1.5&nbsp;million increase in loss resulted primarily from costs related to increased research and development expenses, increased cost of sales resulting from the LTCIP
	and higher personnel expenses resulting from additional personnel employed in pursuit of our growth strategy.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
<A NAME="FIS_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, we had cash and cash equivalents of &euro;2.1&nbsp;million and held investments in three bond funds of
	&euro;30.7&nbsp;million and a note receivable of &euro;1.1&nbsp;million, largely as a result of our initial public offering and our subsequent follow-on offering. These cash
	resources are sufficient to finance our near-term growth strategy, which includes the establishment of additional global service centers as well as to develop our service centers in North America, the
	UK, China and India.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To
	meet the demand for our Services business and to increase capacity, we will require investment in additional printers to be used in our new or expanding Service operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Because
	of our strong liquidity position, we believe that we have the capacity to execute our growth strategy. We have used our cash and capital resources to expand our operations in
	Germany through the purchase in December 2013 of the land and buildings comprising our corporate headquarters, including two new production halls, which will allow us to increase our service center
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	57
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=59,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=950733,FOLIO='57',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]DM76001A.;31',USER='WWASSER',CD='31-MAR-2016;16:47' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DM76001_1_58">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	capacity.
	In addition, we formed a U.S. subsidiary, voxeljet America,&nbsp;Inc., and leased a facility near Detroit, Michigan that houses our North American service center, which began printing
	on-demand parts in the first quarter of 2015. We also used funds for the acquisition of Propshop in October 2014. In 2015, we used our cash to fund the working capital needs of our subsidiaries. For
	2016, we plan to build a new office building as well as new production facilities in Friedberg. This project will be financed by a series of three loans, which were entered into with the
	Kreissparkasse Augsburg, a bank that specializes in providing financing to small and medium-sized businesses. The aggregate amount is &euro;4.0&nbsp;million, which shall be drawn down in
	accordance with the progress of construction work on the project. The amount of each such loan agreement is as follows: (i)&nbsp;&euro;2.0&nbsp;million, with a fixed interest rate of
	2.47% per annum until the end of the term of the loan on December&nbsp;30, 2025, (ii)&nbsp;&euro;1.0&nbsp;million, with a fixed interest rate of 2.72% per annum until the end of the
	term of the loan on December&nbsp;30, 2030, and (iii)&nbsp;&euro;1.0&nbsp;million, with a variable interest rate of 1.75% per annum, which can be terminated by either party with a
	notice period of 3&nbsp;months.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_22"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Cash Flow
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our primary sources of cash in 2015 were our revenues and cash reserves. Our primary uses of cash have traditionally been to finance
	our assets and our working capital.
</FONT>
</P>

<TD ALIGN="RIGHT" VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:0PT;FONT-SIZE:1.5PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
</FONT>
	&#8203;
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;" -->
<FONT>
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:0PT;FONT-SIZE:1.5PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
</FONT>
	&#8203;
<FONT>
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:0PT;FONT-SIZE:1.5PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;" -->
<FONT>

<FONT SIZE=2>
</FONT>
	&#8203;
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_GRID,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;" -->
<FONT>
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:0PT;FONT-SIZE:1.5PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">

<!-- END OF USER-SPECIFIED TAGGED TABLE -->
</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	cash and cash equivalents decreased from &euro;8.0&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2014 to &euro;2.1&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2015, a
	decrease of &euro;5.9&nbsp;million. This was primarily due to our build up in inventory, ramp-up expenses relating to our new subsidiaries as well as a net cash outflow
	of&euro;&nbsp;0.4&nbsp;million related to the restructuring of voxeljet UK.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	cash and cash equivalents decreased from &euro;33.5&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2013 to &euro;8.0&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2014, a
	decrease of &euro;25.5&nbsp;million. This was primarily due to our investment of more than &euro;43&nbsp;million of proceeds from our initial public offering in 2013 and our
	follow-on offering in 2014 in three bond funds. The aim was to achieve a certain amount of interest income at a low risk level for the cash invested.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	April&nbsp;16, 2014, we completed a follow-on offering and received net proceeds of $41.4&nbsp;million or &euro;30.2&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating Activities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net cash used in operating activities was &euro;11.9&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 compared to
	cash used in operating activities of &euro;5.0&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, an increase in cash used of &euro;3.3&nbsp;million. This was
	primarily due to increased working capital requirements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net
	cash used in operating activities was &euro;5.0&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014 compared to cash used in operating activities of
	&euro;1.6&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013, an increase in cash used of &euro;3.4&nbsp;million. This effect was primarily due to higher operating
	costs, including costs to prepare for our initial public offering, partly offset by lower working capital requirements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	58
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=60,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=474798,FOLIO='58',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]DM76001A.;31',USER='WWASSER',CD='31-MAR-2016;16:47' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DM76001_1_59">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Investing Activities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Investing activities consist primarily of setting up infrastructure, including equipment we install and use in our service centers. In
	2015, we invested approximately &euro;1.6&nbsp;million in infrastructure, plant and machinery as well as equipment compared to &euro;2.7&nbsp;million in 2014. We also
	invested more than &euro;43&nbsp;million of proceeds from our equity offerings in 2013 and 2014 in three bond funds in 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Financing Activities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2015, financing cash flows consisted primarily of the redemption from sale and lease back transactions amounting to
	&euro;0.8&nbsp;million as well as the repayment of long-term debt amounting to &euro;0.2&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	2014, financing cash flows consisted principally of the net proceeds we received in our follow-on offering, which amounted to &euro;30.2&nbsp;million, as well as the
	repayment of several loans and financing leases.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	2013, financing cash flows consisted primarily of the net proceeds we received in our initial public offering, which amounted to approximately &euro;47.0&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Financing Agreements
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 we had several lines of credit with four German banks in a total amount of up to
	&euro;0.9&nbsp;million. Interest rates across the credit lines varied from 3.51% to 6.50% as of December&nbsp;31, 2015. There are commitment fees of 0.25% and 0.30% associated with the
	unused portion of two of our lines of credit.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	C.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT, PATENTS AND LICENSES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Research and development is a key part of our strategy to develop new material sets and enhancements to our 3D printers. Our research and development expenses
	totaled &euro;5.5&nbsp;million, &euro;4.0&nbsp;million, and &euro;2.7&nbsp;million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively.
	For further information on our policies and practices regarding research and development, see "Item&nbsp;4.&nbsp;Information on the Company&#151;B. Business Overview&#151;Research
	and Development."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	D.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TREND INFORMATION
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other than as disclosed elsewhere in this annual report, we are not aware of any trends, uncertainties, demands, commitments or events for the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 that are reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on our revenues, profitability, liquidity or capital resources, or that would cause the disclosed financial
	information to be not necessarily indicative of future operating results or financial conditions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	E.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;OFF BALANCE SHEET ARRANGEMENTS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We are not a party to any off balance sheet arrangements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	F.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TABULAR DISCLOSURE OF CONTRACTUAL OBLIGATIONS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Future contractual payments as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 consisted of long- term debt, operating leases and finance leases, which are discussed in greater
	detail below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Leases
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We have historically leased various manufacturing facilities, office and warehouse spaces, equipment and vehicles under operating
	leases. We expect leases that expire to be renewed or replaced by leases on other properties. Rental expense amounted to &euro;0.1&nbsp;million, &euro;0.1&nbsp;million, and
	&euro;0.3&nbsp;million in 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Finance
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our finance leases relate primarily to production machinery. In total, we have entered into sale and leaseback transactions for 17
	self-produced 3D printers, which were sold to banks and leased back to be used in our Services segment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	G.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;SAFE HARBOR
</B>
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	business address of the members of our supervisory board is the same as our business address: voxeljet AG, Paul-Lenz-Stra&szlig;e 1a, 86316 Friedberg, Germany. Our supervisory
	board has determined that all members of our supervisory board are independent under German law and the New York Stock Exchange Listed Company Manual.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	following is a brief summary of the business experience of the members of our supervisory board:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Peter Nietzer
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, born in 1960 in Heilbronn, Germany, has been the chairman of our supervisory board since July&nbsp;2, 2013.
	Mr.&nbsp;Nietzer has served as owner and managing director of KITES Industriebeteiligungen&nbsp;GmbH, a private investment holding company, and of M59 Advisory Services, since January 2013 and as
	Partner and Chief Financial Officer of GermanCapital&nbsp;GmbH, a private
	equity company he co-founded and that specializes in mid-market buy-outs, since July 2005. Mr.&nbsp;Nietzer has served as a Non-Executive Director of Cognis Credit Opportunities Fund&nbsp;Ltd.,
	Cognis Credit Opportunities Master Fund&nbsp;Ltd. and Cognis Credit Opportunities Manager (Cayman)&nbsp;Ltd. since September 2013. Since April 2000, Mr.&nbsp;Nietzer has been an executive board
	member and Managing Partner of Felicitas&nbsp;GmbH (which was previously known as GI Ventures AG), a fund management company he helped found. Mr.&nbsp;Nietzer served as a Managing Director in the
	private equity unit of PartnersGroup AG from January to October 2011. Mr.&nbsp;Nietzer holds a M.B.A. from Friedrich-Alexander University Erlangen-N&uuml;rnberg, Germany. We believe that
	Mr.&nbsp;Nietzer's over 13&nbsp;years of experience in private equity and his previous roles as a supervisory board member provide him with valuable insight into our business, particularly in the
	areas of financing and acquisition opportunities, while his focus on technology companies gives him insight into our operations and industry. In addition, Mr.&nbsp;Nietzer's work as a chief
	financial officer provides the supervisory board with expertise in financial matters.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Dr.&nbsp;Stefan S&ouml;hn
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, born in 1954 in D&uuml;sseldorf, Germany, has been the vice chairman of our supervisory
	board since July&nbsp;2, 2013. Since January 2010, Dr.&nbsp;S&ouml;hn has served as a Partner and Managing Director of MBL China Consulting&nbsp;GmbH, as owner and manager of
	S&ouml;hn Industrial Consulting and as Of Counsel Lawyer and Head of China Desk of Sonntag&nbsp;&amp; Partner Wirtschaftspr&uuml;fer, Steuerberater, Rechtsanw&auml;lte in
	Augsburg and Munich, Germany. Dr.&nbsp;S&ouml;hn held executive positions at KUKA Systems GmbH, an equipment supplier to the automotive industry, from July 2000 to December 2009, serving
	as its Chief Financial Officer from July 2000 to December 2006 and as its Chief Executive Officer from January 2007 to December 2009. During his time at KUKA Systems&nbsp;GmbH,
	Dr.&nbsp;S&ouml;hn led the successful expansion of its business in Asia. Dr.&nbsp;S&ouml;hn also serves as the deputy chairman of the supervisory board of
	Mocopinus&nbsp;GmbH&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Co. KG. Dr.&nbsp;S&ouml;hn holds a law degree from the University of Augsburg, Germany and a Master of Science in Management for the
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	61
</FONT>
</P>

<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DO76001_1_62">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	London
	Business School. We believe that Dr.&nbsp;S&ouml;hn's business experience in the automotive industry and in expanding corporate operations into Asia will assist us as we seek to
	grow our business. In addition, we believe that Dr.&nbsp;S&ouml;hn's various experiences throughout his career, including his work as an attorney, chief financial officer and member of the
	supervisory boards of several companies, including public companies, provides our supervisory board with a broad range of knowledge and insight.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Prof. Dr.&nbsp;Joachim Heinzl
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, born in 1940 in Aussig in what is now the Czech Republic, has been a member of our supervisory board
	since July&nbsp;2, 2013. Prof. Dr.&nbsp;Heinzl has served as Professor Emeritus at the Technical University of Munich, Germany since 2005. Prior to becoming Professor Emeritus, Prof.
	Dr.&nbsp;Heinzl had been the Chair for Precision Engineering and Micro Technology at the Technical University of Munich since 1978 and served the Technical University of Munich as Vice-Dean and Dean
	of the Faculty of Mechanical Engineering from 1988 to 1992 and as First Vice President from 1995 to 2002. Prof. Dr.&nbsp;Heinzl focused a large portion of his research on technology relating to
	3D&nbsp;printing while on the faculty of the Technical University of Munich. From 2006 to 2012, Prof. Dr.&nbsp;Heinzl was the President of the Bavarian Research Foundation. Prof. Dr.&nbsp;Heinzl
	has been a foreign associate of the U.S. National Academy of Engineering since 2007. Prof. Dr.&nbsp;Heinzl also co-founded our
	company as Generis&nbsp;GmbH in 1999. Prof. Dr.&nbsp;Heinzl holds a diploma in mechanical engineering and a doctorate in electroacoustics from the Technical University of Munich. We believe that
	Prof. Dr.&nbsp;Heinzl's vast knowledge of technical and engineering matters, including 3D printing technology, provides our supervisory board with additional insight into the technical details of
	our operations and industry.
</FONT>
</P>

	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Dr.&nbsp;Ingo Ederer
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, born in 1967 in Weilheim, Germany, is one of our founders and is the key inventor of our technology. He has served
	as our Chief Executive Officer since 2013. Dr.&nbsp;Ederer co-founded our company as Generis&nbsp;GmbH in 1999 and served as our Managing Director from our incorporation in 1999 to 2013, building
	up the company from the start-up phase to become a leading provider of 3D&nbsp;printers for industrial and commercial customers. After graduating with a degree in mechanical engineering from the
	Technical University of Munich in 1993, Dr.&nbsp;Ederer started his career as researcher at the department of precision engineering at the Technical University of Munich where he received his Ph.D.
	in 2000 with a thesis on piezo-based micro-jetting devices. He contributes more than 20&nbsp;years of experience in the 3D printing equipment market and is a holder of more than 50 patents in the
	field of 3D printing.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Rudolf Franz
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, born in 1967 in Friedberg, Germany, has served as our Chief Financial Officer since 2013. Mr.&nbsp;Franz, through his
	venture fund, Franz Industriebeteiligungen AG, has been one of our shareholders since 2003 and served as our Chief Operating Officer from 2003 to 2013, focusing on building our global sales and
	finance, accounting and administration structures. Mr.&nbsp;Franz has been the chairman of the supervisory board of Rettenmeier Holding AG since 2011. From 2007 to 2009, Mr.&nbsp;Franz served as
	the Managing Director of Hama Holding&nbsp;GmbH and was the chairman of the
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	62
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=64,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=898976,FOLIO='62',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]DO76001A.;16',USER='MKEANE',CD='31-MAR-2016;15:27' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DO76001_1_63">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">

	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	supervisory
	board of Wavelight AG from 2005 to 2009. In 1995, Mr.&nbsp;Franz was appointed as investment manager of Technologieholding VC&nbsp;GmbH, an international venture capital fund that
	invested in European technologies, and became partner in 1997, where he was responsible for managing the Munich investment team. After he sold his shares in Technologieholding VC&nbsp;GmbH to 3i
	Group&nbsp;plc in 2000, Mr.&nbsp;Franz served as Managing Director of 3i Group&nbsp;plc and was responsible for technology investments in the German-speaking market from 2000 to 2002.
	Mr.&nbsp;Franz studied political economics and industrial engineering at the University of Augsburg and the University of Munich and earned a master's degree from the University of Applied Science
	Munich in 1991.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;COMPENSATION
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Compensation of Management Board Members
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We have entered into service agreements with the current members of our management board. These agreements generally provide for an
	annual fixed compensation (base salary), an annual performance award (annual bonus) with a target of up to 40% of the yearly base salary, as well as a long-term performance award for a
	three-business-year period (long-term bonus) with a target of up to 60% of the yearly base salary. The performance targets of the annual and long-term bonuses are a mixture of certain financial and
	non-financial targets, such as revenue and profitability goals, as well as a certain increase of the price of our ADSs. In addition to the fixed and variable remuneration components, under the terms
	of their service agreements, the members of our management board are entitled to additional benefits (including company car arrangements, mobile phone, accident and director and officer liability
	insurance) and reimbursement of necessary and reasonable expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	believe that the service agreements between us and the members of our management board provide for payments and benefits (including upon termination of employment) that are in line
	with customary market practice for similar companies who are operating in our industry.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	2016, the two members of our management board are collectively entitled to receive total compensation of up to kEUR 766, which includes base salary, bonus payments and other
	compensation as a result of other benefits as described above. In 2015, the two members of our management board
	collectively received total compensation of kEUR 506, which included base salary and other compensation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Compensation of Supervisory Board Members in the Business Year 2015
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In our annual general meeting on May&nbsp;27, 2014 the following remuneration system was
	resolved:
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Ordinary members of the supervisory board receive a fixed remuneration in the amount of &euro;30,000 per annum. The
	chairman and vice chairman of the supervisory board shall receive a higher fixed remuneration in the amount of &euro;60,000 per annum and &euro;45,000 per annum, respectively.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We do not pay fees for attendance at supervisory board meetings.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The members of the supervisory board are entitled to reimbursement of their reasonable, documented expenses (including, but not
	limited to, travel, board and lodging and telecommunication expenses).
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This
	remuneration system will remain in force until it has been amended or terminated by our general shareholders' meeting.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	63
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=65,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=184472,FOLIO='63',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]DO76001A.;16',USER='MKEANE',CD='31-MAR-2016;15:27' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DO76001_1_64">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	C.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;BOARD PRACTICES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Overview
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We are a German stock corporation (
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Aktiengesellschaft
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, or
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	AG
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	) with our registered seat in
	Germany. We are subject to German legislation on stock corporations, most importantly the German Stock Corporation Act
	(
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Aktiengesetz,
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	or
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	AktG
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	). In accordance with the German Stock Corporation Act
	(
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Aktiengesetz
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	), our corporate bodies are the management board (
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Vorstand
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	), the supervisory board
	(
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Aufsichtsrat
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	) and the shareholders' meeting (
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Hauptversammlung
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	). Our management board and our
	supervisory board are entirely separate and, as a rule, no individual may simultaneously be a member of both boards.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	management board is responsible for the day-to-day management of our business in accordance with applicable laws, our articles of association
	(
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Satzung
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	) and the management board's internal rules of procedure (
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Gesch&auml;ftsordnung
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	). Our
	management board represents us in our dealings with third parties.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	principal function of our supervisory board is to supervise our management board. The supervisory board is also responsible for appointing and removing the members of our management
	board and representing us in connection with transactions between a current or former member of the management board and us.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Under
	German law, members of both boards owe a duty of loyalty and care to us. In carrying out their duties, they are required to exercise the standard of care of a prudent and diligent
	businessperson. If they fail to observe the appropriate standard of care, they may become liable to us.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	carrying out their duties, the members of both boards may take into account a broad range of considerations when making decisions, including our interests and the interests of our
	shareholders, employees, creditors and, to a limited extent, the general public, while respecting the rights of our shareholders to be treated on equal terms. Additionally, the management board is
	responsible for implementing an internal monitoring system for risk management purposes.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	supervisory board has comprehensive monitoring responsibilities. To ensure that our supervisory board can carry out these functions properly, our management board must, among other
	things,
	regularly report to our supervisory board regarding our current business operations and future business planning (including financial, investment and personnel planning). In addition, our supervisory
	board is entitled to request special reports from the management board at any time.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Under
	German law, our shareholders have no direct recourse against the members of our management board or our supervisory board if they have breached their duty of loyalty and care to
	us. Apart from insolvency or other special circumstances, only the company has the ability to claim damages against the members of our two boards. We may waive these claims to damages or settle these
	claims only if at least three years have passed since any violation of a duty occurred and only if our shareholders approve the waiver or settlement at a shareholders' meeting with a simple majority
	of the votes cast; provided that shareholders who in the aggregate hold one-tenth or more of our share capital do not oppose the waiver or settlement and have their opposition formally recorded in the
	meeting's minutes by a German civil law notary.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	following description, as far as it relates to our articles of association, is based on the articles of association, as adopted by our general shareholders' meeting on May&nbsp;22,
	2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Supervisory Board
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our supervisory board currently consists of three members, which is the minimum number of members allowed under German law. As we grow,
	our supervisory board may be required to include
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	64
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=66,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=677850,FOLIO='64',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]DO76001A.;16',USER='MKEANE',CD='31-MAR-2016;15:27' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DO76001_1_65">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	employee
	representatives subject to the provisions of the German One-Third Employee Representation Act (
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Drittelbeteiligungsgesetz
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	) and the German
	Codetermination Act (
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Mitbestimmungsgesetz
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Currently,
	all of the members of our supervisory board are elected by the shareholders' meeting in accordance with the provisions of the German Stock Corporation Act
	(
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Aktiengesetz
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	). German law does not require the majority of our supervisory board members to be independent. The rules of procedure for our supervisory
	board provide that the supervisory board should be composed of a majority of independent members, as determined by the supervisory board. Under the supervisory board's rules of procedure, a board
	member is deemed to be independent if such member has no business or personal relationships with us or the management board that could constitute a conflict of interest.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Under
	German law, the members of a supervisory board may be elected for a term of up to approximately five years, depending on the dates of the annual general meeting at which the
	members of the supervisory board are elected, which is the standard term of office. Reelection, including repeated reelection, is permissible. The shareholders' meeting may specify a term of office
	for individual members or all of the members of our supervisory board which is shorter than the standard term of office and, subject to statutory limits, may set different start and end dates for the
	terms of members of our supervisory board. All members of our supervisory board were elected by our annual general meeting on May&nbsp;27, 2014 for a term that ends on the day of the shareholders'
	meeting, which resolves on the discharge of the supervisory board for the business year 2018.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	shareholders' meeting may, at the same time as it elects the members of the supervisory board, elect one or more substitute members. The substitute members replace members who cease
	to be members of our supervisory board and take their place for the remainder of their respective terms of office. We have not elected any substitute members.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Members
	of our supervisory board may be dismissed at any time during their term of office by a resolution of the shareholders' meeting adopted by a simple majority of the votes cast. In
	addition, any member of our supervisory board may resign at any time by giving one month written notice of his or her resignation to the chairperson of our supervisory board (in case the chairperson
	resigns, such notice is to be given to the vice chairperson). Our supervisory board may agree upon a shorter notice period. None of the members of the supervisory board are eligible to receive any
	benefits upon termination of their service on the supervisory board.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	supervisory board elects a chairperson and a vice chairperson from its members. The vice chairperson exercises the chairperson's rights and obligations whenever the chairperson is
	unable to do so. On May&nbsp;27, 2013, Peter Nietzer, Dr.&nbsp;Stefan S&ouml;hn and Prof. Dr.&nbsp;Joachim Heinzl were appointed as members of our supervisory board. The members of our
	supervisory board have elected Peter Nietzer as chairperson and Dr.&nbsp;Stefan S&ouml;hn as vice chairperson, each for the term of their respective membership on our supervisory board.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	supervisory board meets at least twice during the first half and twice during the second half of each fiscal year. Our articles of association and the supervisory board's rules of
	procedure provide that a quorum of the supervisory board members is present if at least half of its members, but in any case no less than three members, participate in the vote. Members of our
	supervisory board are deemed present if they participate via telephone or video conference, subject to no other member of the supervisory board raising any objection to this type of participation. Any
	absent member may also participate in the voting by submitting his or her written vote through another member.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Resolutions
	of our supervisory board are passed by the vote of a simple majority unless otherwise required by law, our articles of association or the rules of procedure of our
	supervisory board. In the event of a tie, the chairperson casts the tie-breaking vote.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	65
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>

</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	supervisory board is not permitted to make management decisions, but, in accordance with German law and in addition to its statutory responsibilities, it has determined that the
	following matters, among others, require its prior consent:
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	any material changes to our business strategy;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the purchase or sale of real estate or legal entities or the purchase, sale, creation, extension, reduction or termination of business
	activities, including tangible or intangible assets, if the relevant price or value, in each case, exceeds &euro;50,000;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the purchase, sale or creation of joint ventures;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the termination of, or amendment to, consulting, advisory or other service agreements, if our costs or obligations associated with
	such agreement exceed &euro;50,000 per year or &euro;250,000 in the aggregate;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the termination of, or amendment to, operating leases, land leases or rental agreements in relation to real estate, buildings or
	similar objects, if our obligations associated with such agreement exceed &euro;50,000 per year or &euro;250,000 in the aggregate;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>

</FONT>

</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	any hiring, dismissal or modification of an employment agreement of any executive manager, provided that their aggregate cash
	remuneration (including cash bonuses) exceeds &euro;75,000;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>

</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>

</FONT>
</DT>

<FONT SIZE=2>
	any material change or amendment to our code of conduct; and
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the approval of our budget.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	supervisory board may designate further types of actions requiring its approval.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Section&nbsp;2(2)
	of the rules of procedure of our supervisory board provides that a supervisory board member may not continue to serve on our supervisory board past their
	75th&nbsp;birthday.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Supervisory Board Practices
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Decisions are generally made by our supervisory board as a whole; however, decisions on certain matters may be delegated to committees
	of our supervisory board to the extent permitted by law. The chairperson, or if he or she is prevented from doing so, the vice chairperson, chairs the meetings of the supervisory board and determines
	the order in which the agenda items are discussed, the method and order of the voting, any adjournment of the discussion and passing of resolutions on individual agenda items after a due assessment of
	the circumstances.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant
	to Section&nbsp;107(3) AktG, the supervisory board may form committees from among its members and charge them with the performance of specific tasks. The committees' tasks,
	authorizations and processes are determined by the supervisory board. Where permissible by law, important powers of the supervisory board may also be transferred to committees.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Under
	Article&nbsp;7 of its internal rules of procedure, the supervisory board has set up and appointed a Compensation and Nomination Committee and an Audit Committee.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	66
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=6,SEQ=68,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=501865,FOLIO='66',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]DO76001A.;16',USER='MKEANE',CD='31-MAR-2016;15:27' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DO76001_1_67">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">

	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Compensation and Nomination Committee
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant to our articles of association and the rules of procedure of our supervisory board, the Compensation and Nomination Committee
	prepares hiring and personnel decisions for approval by the supervisory board and performs the following functions:
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	preparation of the resolutions of the supervisory board regarding the conclusion, alteration and termination of service contracts of
	members of the management board within the framework of the compensation system adopted by the supervisory board;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	preparation of the resolutions of the supervisory board to increase or reduce the compensation paid to the management board under
	Section&nbsp;87 para. 2 AktG;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	preparation of the resolutions of the supervisory board regarding the framework of the compensation scheme of the management board,
	including its essential contractual elements, and providing the supervisory board with information necessary for it to review this compensation scheme on a regular basis;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	representation of the company vis-&agrave;-vis former members of the management board under Section&nbsp;112 AktG;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	granting consent for secondary occupations (including the acceptance of seats on supervisory boards of other companies) and for other
	activities of management board members under Section&nbsp;88 AktG;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	approval of agreements with supervisory board members under Section&nbsp;114 AktG; and
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	proposing suitable candidates as supervisory board members to the shareholders' meeting in case of elections of supervisory board
	members.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	Compensation and Nomination Committee monitors the management board's adherence to the rules of procedure of the management board. The rules of procedure of the management board
	contain, among other things, obligations for the management board to provide certain information to the Compensation and Nomination Committee.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All
	current members of the supervisory board are members of the Compensation and Nomination Committee. Our supervisory board has determined that each member of the Compensation and
	Nomination Committee satisfies the independence requirements of the New York Stock Exchange.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Audit Committee
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our Audit Committee assists the supervisory board in overseeing the accuracy and integrity of our accounting and financial reporting
	processes and audits of our financial statements, the effectiveness of the internal control system and our compliance with legal and regulatory requirements, the independent auditors' qualifications
	and independence and the performance of the independent auditors.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	Audit Committee's duties and responsibilities to carry out its purposes include, among others:
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the review of our accounting processes;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the review of the effectiveness of our internal systems of control, risk management and compliance;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the review and the handling of matters and processes related to auditor independence;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the recommendation of the auditors for approval by the shareholders' meeting, the commissioning of the auditors to conduct the audit,
	agreeing on additional services to be provided by the auditors under the auditor's assignment, the establishment of the scope and the
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	67
</FONT>
</P>

	review points of the audit, agreeing upon a fee with the auditors and oversight of the auditors' work (including resolution of disagreements with the auditors);

	the preparation of the supervisory board's resolution on our financial statements;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>

<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	reviewing our interim financial statements that are made public or otherwise filed with any securities regulatory authority;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	discussing any flaws relating to our internal control systems, as reported by the supervisory board to the Audit Committee;
</FONT>

</FONT>
