</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	3. Summary of significant accounting policies (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	present
	value of minimum lease payments and depreciated over the asset's estimated useful life. Assets under finance leases are included in "Property, plant and equipment" in the statement of
	financial position. Gains on sale and leaseback transactions are recorded as deferred income in the statement of financial position and recognized as "Other operating income" over the respective lease
	term.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating
	leases consist of various lease agreements for the rental of manufacturing facilities, office and warehouse space, vehicles, and office and IT equipment, expiring in various
	years through 2020. Rent expense under operating leases is charged to profit or loss on a straight-line basis over the term of the lease.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	also
	rents certain of its 3D printers to customers under operating leases.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	2015,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	leased five 3D printers (2014: three 3D printers and 2013: four 3D printers) to customers under operating leases. Rental
	income is recognized on a straight-line basis over the term of the lease as revenue and is reported within the Systems segment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Long Term Cash Incentive Plan
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	has a Long-Term Cash Incentive Plan ("LTCIP"), a cash-settled share-based
	payment arrangement, that provides for cash awards to non-executive employees. Compensation cost is determined based on the grant-date fair value of the awards and recognized, net of estimated
	forfeitures due to termination of employment, on a straight-line basis over the requisite service period of the award and depending on the evaluation of certain performance and market conditions. The
	requisite service period is generally the vesting period stated in the award. The liability for these awards is measured at fair value at each reporting date until settlement and is classified within
	"other liabilities and provisions in the consolidated statement of financial position.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Foreign currencies
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The financial statements are presented in Euros, the functional currency of
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet&nbsp;AG
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Monetary
	transactions denominated in foreign currencies are translated to Euros at the exchange rates prevailing on the transaction date.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	financial statements of foreign subsidiaries are translated using the concept of the functional currency in accordance with IAS&nbsp;21. The assets and liabilities of foreign
	subsidiaries are translated at the spot rate at the end of the period, while their income statement items are translated at average exchange rates for the respective periods. All resulting exchange
	differences are recognized in other comprehensive income. Gains and losses on foreign currency transactions are shown within other operating income and other operating expenses, respectively, in the
	consolidated statement of comprehensive loss.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	loans provided to
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet AG
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	's subsidiaries
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	and
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet America
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	are not considered as net
	investment. Consequently, gains or losses from foreign exchange differences thereon are recognized in other
	operating income or expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-10
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income Tax
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income tax expense (benefit) consists of current and deferred tax expense and benefit in accordance with IAS&nbsp;12.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Current
	income tax expense (benefit) is based on taxable profit (loss) for the year. Taxable profit (loss) differs from profit (loss) as reported in the statements of comprehensive
	income (loss) because it excludes items of income or expense that are taxable or deductible in other years and further excludes items that are never taxable or deductible. Current income tax expense
	(benefit) is calculated using tax rates that have been enacted or substantively enacted by the end of the respective reporting period.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Deferred
	income tax expense (benefit) is recognized on temporary differences between the carrying amounts of assets and liabilities in the statement of financial position and the
	corresponding tax basis used in the computation of taxable profit (loss).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Deferred
	tax liabilities are generally recognized for all taxable temporary differences and deferred tax assets, including for carry forward losses to the extent that it is probable that
	taxable profits will be available against which deductible temporary differences can be utilized. The carrying amount of deferred tax assets is reviewed at the end of each reporting period and reduced
	to the extent that it is no longer more probable than not that sufficient taxable profits will be available to allow all or a part of the assets to be recovered.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Deferred
	tax expense (benefit) is calculated at the tax rates that are expected to apply in the periods when the liability is settled or the asset is realized, based on tax rates (and
	tax regulations) that have been enacted or substantively enacted by the end of the reporting period. The measurement of deferred tax liabilities and assets reflects the tax consequences that would
	follow from the manner in which the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	expects, at the end of the reporting period, to recover or settle the carrying amount of its assets and
	liabilities. Deferred tax expense (benefit) is charged or credited to profit or loss, except when it relates to items charged or credited directly to equity, in which case the deferred taxation is
	also recorded to equity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-11
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	3. Summary of significant accounting policies (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Deferred
	tax assets and liabilities are offset when there is a legally enforceable right to set off tax assets against tax liabilities and when they relate to income taxes levied by the
	same taxation authority and the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	intends to settle its current tax assets and liabilities on a net basis.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Intangible Assets
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Intangible assets, including software, licenses and customer relationships, that are acquired by the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	and have a finite useful life
	are measured at cost less accumulated amortization and any impairment losses. Amortization for intangible assets
	with finite useful lives is recognized on a straight-line basis over their useful lives. The amortization for the customer list and digital library arising from the purchase price allocation related
	to the acquisition of our subsidiary
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, was presented within selling expenses and cost of sales, respectively. Goodwill arising from the
	acquisition of subsidiaries is not amortized and is measured at cost less accumulated impairment losses. Goodwill is tested annually for impairment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	estimated useful economic lives of acquired intangible assets are presented in the following table:
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_35"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">

<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	USEFUL LIFE OF INTANGIBLE ASSETS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;WIDTH:80%;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
</FONT>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;An
	intangible asset is derecognized upon disposal or when no future economic benefits are expected to arise from the continued use of the asset. Any gain or loss arising on derecognition
	of the asset (calculated as the difference between the net disposal proceeds and the carrying amount of the item) is included in profit or loss in the period in which the item is derecognized.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Property, Plant and Equipment
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Property, plant and equipment is carried at acquisition or manufacturing cost (for internally manufactured printers used in the
	Services segment) and depreciated on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the related assets, taking into account estimated residual values. Realized gains and losses are
	recognized upon disposal or retirement of the related assets and are reflected within other operating income or other operating expenses in the consolidated statement of comprehensive loss. Subsequent
	expenditures are capitalized only if it is probable that
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	will receive additional economic benefits from the particular asset associated with
	these expenditures, and the costs can be determined reliably. Repair and maintenance expenditures are expensed as incurred. Leased assets are depreciated over the shorter of the lease term and their
	useful lives unless it is reasonably certain that the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	will obtain ownership by the end of the lease
	term. Land is not depreciated. Additions to property, plant and equipment relating to self-constructed 3D printers are considered non-cash transactions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-12
</FONT>
</P>

</TD>
<TD ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	7-8&nbsp;years
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="WHITE" VALIGN="BOTTOM">
<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-LEFT:10PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Printers leased to customers under operating lease
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	7-8&nbsp;years
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#CCEEFF" VALIGN="BOTTOM">
<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-LEFT:10PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Other facilities, machinery and factory equipment
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	2-20&nbsp;years
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="WHITE" VALIGN="BOTTOM">
<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-LEFT:10PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Office equipment
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	3-12&nbsp;years
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<!-- END OF USER-SPECIFIED TAGGED TABLE -->
</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Useful
	lives, depreciation methods and residual values are reviewed at least annually and, in case they change significantly, depreciation charges for current and future periods are
	adjusted accordingly.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Inventories
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Raw materials
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Raw materials are measured at the lower of acquisition cost, as determined on the first-in, first-out (FIFO) method, and net realizable
	value.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Work in progress and finished goods
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Work in progress and finished goods are measured at the lower of manufacturing cost and net realizable value. Manufacturing costs
	comprise all costs that are directly attributable to the manufacturing process, such as direct material and labor, and production related overheads (based on normal operating capacity and normal
	consumption of material, labor and other production costs), including depreciation charges.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net
	realizable value is defined as the estimated selling price in the ordinary course of business less the estimated costs of completion and the estimated costs necessary to make the
	sale. For purposes of determining net realizable value, selling expenses include all costs expected to be incurred to make the sale, primarily shipping, packaging and handling as well as commissions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Obsolete
	inventories are written off directly into cost of sales.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Impairment of non-financial assets
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	assesses at the end of each reporting period whether there is an indication
	that a non-financial asset may be impaired. The asset is tested for impairment if there are indicators that the carrying amounts may not be recoverable. An impairment loss is recognized in the amount
	by which the asset's carrying amount exceeds its recoverable amount. The recoverable amount is defined as the higher of an asset's fair value less cost to sell and its value in use.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If
	the fair value less cost to sell cannot be determined, or if it is lower than the carrying amount, the value in use is calculated. The value in use is calculated by discounting the
	future expected cash flows at a risk-adequate pre-tax interest rate, current and expected future cash flows are taken into account, together with technological, economic and general development
	trends, on the basis of approved and adjusted financial plans.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-13
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=7,SEQ=112,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=958723,FOLIO='F-13',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]FM76001A.;22',USER='JLAWRENA',CD='31-MAR-2016;17:41' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_FM76001_1_14">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	3. Summary of significant accounting policies (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Financial instruments
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Non-derivative financial assets and liabilities
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	classifies non-derivative financial assets into the following categories:
	financial assets at fair value through profit or loss, held-to-maturity financial assets, loans and receivables and available-for-sale financial assets.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Available-for-sale
	financial assets are initially measured at fair value plus any directly attributable transaction costs. Subsequent to initial recognition, they are measured at fair
	value and changes therein, other than impairment losses and foreign currency differences on debt instruments, are recognized in other comprehensive income and accumulated in the fair value reserve.
	When these assets are derecognized, the gain or loss accumulated in equity is reclassified to profit or loss in other operating income or expense.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Loans
	and receivables are financial assets with fixed or determinable payments that are not quoted in an active market. Such assets are recognized initially at fair value. Subsequent to
	initial recognition, loans and receivables are measured at amortized cost using the effective interest method, less any impairment losses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Non-derivative
	financial liabilities are initially measured at fair value less any directly attributable transaction costs. Subsequent to initial recognition, these liabilities are
	measured at amortized cost using the effective interest method. The
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	does not elect to measure financial liabilities at fair value through profit
	or loss.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Impairment
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Financial assets not classified as at fair value through profit or loss are assessed at each reporting date to determine whether there
	is objective evidence of impairment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For
	financial assets measured at amortized cost, an impairment loss is calculated as the difference between an asset's carrying amount and the present value of the estimated future cash
	flows discounted at the asset's original effective interest rate. Losses are recognized in profit or loss and reflected in an allowance account. When the Group considers that there are no realistic
	prospects of recovery of the asset, the relevant amounts are written off. If the amount of impairment loss subsequently decreases and the decrease can be related objectively to an event occurring
	after the impairment was recognized, then the previously recognized impairment loss is reversed through profit or loss.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Impairment
	losses on available-for-sale financial assets are recognized by reclassifying the losses accumulated in the fair value reserve to profit or loss. The amount reclassified is
	the difference between the acquisition cost (net of any principal repayment and amortization) and the current fair value, less any impairment loss previously recognized in profit or loss.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Cash and cash equivalents
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cash and cash equivalents are short-term bank deposits and are not subject to a significant risk of change in value.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-14
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=8,SEQ=113,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=371830,FOLIO='F-14',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]FM76001A.;22',USER='JLAWRENA',CD='31-MAR-2016;17:41' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_FM76001_1_15">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	3. Summary of significant accounting policies (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Deferred income
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Deferred income from sale and leaseback
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gains resulting from deferred income from 3D printers sold and leased back under finance leases are recognized within other operating
	income in the consolidated statement of comprehensive loss over the respective lease term.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Deferred income from extended warranty contracts
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Extended warranty contract revenue is recognized on a straight-line basis per month as the costs of providing services incurred under
	the contracts generally do not vary significantly over the contract term.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Earnings (loss) per share
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Basic earnings per share amounts are calculated by dividing profit (loss) by the weighted average number of ordinary shares
	outstanding. There are no dilutive instruments issued and outstanding.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	4. New standards and interpretations not yet adopted
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The IASB issued a number of new IFRS standards which are required to be adopted in annual periods beginning after December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>

</FONT>
</TD>

<TR BGCOLOR="#CCEEFF" VALIGN="TOP">

<FONT SIZE=2>

<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Amendment Accounting for Acquisitions of Interests in Joint Operations
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="WHITE" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-LEFT:10PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	IAS&nbsp;27
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=2>
	01/2016
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Amendment Equity Method in Separate Financial Statements
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	5. Critical accounting judgment and key sources of estimation and uncertainty
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In the process of applying the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company'
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	s accounting policies, Management is required to make judgments, estimates and assumptions about
	the carrying amounts of assets and liabilities that are not readily apparent from other sources. These estimates and associated assumptions are based on the knowledge available as of the preparation
	date of the financial statements and historical experiences as well as other factors that are considered to be relevant. The estimates and underlying assumptions are reviewed on an ongoing basis.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Developments
	outside Management's control may cause actual amounts to differ from the original estimates. In that case, the underlying assumptions and, if necessary, the carrying amounts
	of the pertinent assets and liabilities are adjusted accordingly. Revisions to accounting estimates are recognized in the period in which the estimate is revised, if the revision affects only that
	period, or in the period of the revision and future periods, if the revision affects both current and future periods.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	assumptions and estimates refer primarily to the recognition of revenue, the determination of the useful lives of property, plant and equipment, the application of the criteria for
	recognizing finance leases, the realization of receivables and customer loans, measurement of inventory, the recognition and measurement of provisions, the recognition and measurement of share based
	payment liabilities (LTCIP), and the impairment of goodwill.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	key assumptions concerning the future and other key sources of estimation uncertainty at the end of the reporting period, that have a significant risk of causing a material
	adjustment to the carrying amounts of assets and liabilities within the next financial year are discussed below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Revenue recognition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Revenue on sales of machines is recognized when the significant risks and rewards of ownership are transferred to the customer, the
	amount of revenue and cost incurred or to be incurred can be measured reliably and it is probable that the economic benefits associated with the sale will flow to the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On occasion, we grant a
	loan for a portion or all of the purchase price of a machine to a customer. We recognize revenue on such sales when it
	is probable that we will obtain the economic benefits from the transaction. In these situations, we analyze the credit risk associated with the customer based on all available information and the
	outstanding balance to determine the risk. The amount of revenue comprises the fair value of the consideration received, including future payments under the loan agreement. We typically retain legal
	title to our machines until receipt of all consideration to protect the collectability of any outstanding balances due, which does not preclude a conclusion that the significant risks and rewards of
	ownership have transferred.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Useful lives of intangible assets and property, plant and equipment
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The estimated useful lives and amortization or depreciation methods for intangible assets and property, plant and equipment are based
	on the experience of the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	with similar assets that are used in a similar way. Additional amortization or depreciation, as applicable, is
	recorded if the estimated useful lives and/or the residual values are different from the previous estimation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Criteria for classifying leases
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A finance lease is an arrangement that transfers substantially all the risks and rewards incident to ownership of an asset to the
	lessee. Whether a lease is a finance lease or an operating lease depends
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-16
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=10,SEQ=115,EFW="2228079",CP="VOXELJET AG",DN="1",CHK=620902,FOLIO='F-16',FILE='DISK129:[16ZAV1.16ZAV76001]FM76001A.;22',USER='JLAWRENA',CD='31-MAR-2016;17:41' -->
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_FM76001_1_17">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	5. Critical accounting judgment and key sources of estimation and uncertainty (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	on
	the substance of the transaction rather than the form of the contract. The criteria to classify a lease as a finance lease are as follows (one criterion is sufficient to meet the classification as
	a finance lease):
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	1.
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the
	lease transfers ownership of the asset to the lessee by the end of the lease term;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	2.
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the
	lessee has a bargain purchase option and it is reasonably certain at the date of inception that the option will be exercised;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	3.
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the
	lease term is for the major part of the economic life of the asset even if title is not transferred;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	4.
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	at
	the inception of the lease the present value of the minimum lease payments amounts to substantially all of the fair value of the leased asset;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	5.
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the
	leased asset is of such a specialized nature that only the lessee can use it without major modifications;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	6.
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	gains
	or losses from the fluctuation in the fair value of the residual accrue to the lessee;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	7.
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the
	lessee has the ability to continue the lease for a secondary period at a rent that is substantially lower than market rent; and
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	8.
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	if
	the lessee can cancel the lease, our associated losses are borne by the lessee.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All
	of our leaseback arrangements for 3D printers transfer ownership of the asset to the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	at the end of the lease term, therefore,
	these leases are accounted for as finance leases.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Trade receivables
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	evaluates customer accounts with past-due outstanding balances or specific
	accounts for which it has information that the customer may be unable to meet its financial obligations. Based upon a review of these accounts and Management's analysis and judgment, the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	estimates the future cash flows expected to be recovered from these receivables. The amount of the impairment on doubtful receivables is
	measured individually and recorded as a specific allowance against that customer's receivable balance so as to equal the amount expected to be recovered. The allowance is re-evaluated and adjusted
	periodically as additional information is received.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Inventories
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Management reviews inventories on a product-by-product basis at the end of each reporting period to identify obsolete inventory items
	that are no longer suitable for use in production. Management estimates the net realizable value of finished goods, work-in progress and raw materials primarily based on current market conditions and
	on its experience in manufacturing and selling products of a similar nature. If net realizable value is lower than cost, an allowance is recorded.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Provisions and other liabilities
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Provisions are recognized and measured on the basis of the estimate and probability of future outflows of resources embodying benefits,
	as well as based on the circumstances known at the end of the reporting period. Assumptions also are made as to the probabilities whether and within what ranges the provisions may be used. The
	assessment of whether a present obligation exists is generally based on assessments of internal experts. Estimates can change on the basis of new information and the actual charges may affect the
	performance and financial position of the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-17
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

	Table of Contents

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Impairment of goodwill
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The estimates related to the impairment of goodwill arising from the acquisition of
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
	UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	included the consideration of revenue and expenses in the underlying business plan. In addition, the interest rate used in the discounted cash flow model as well as the
	growth rate applied in the terminal value are subject to assumptions, uncertainties and judgments. As part of the preparation of the impairment test, Management used historical data regarding
	revenues, sale prices and expenses as well as forecasts related to the UK economy and its industry. Information regarding comparable companies in the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company's
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	peer group was also considered.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	a result of the restructuring of the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	business, an impairment of raw materials and work in progress in the amount of
	&euro;1.1&nbsp;million was recognized in 2015. No impairments of inventories were recorded in 2014 and 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	of December&nbsp;31, 2014, within work in progress there was one unfinished VX4000 3D printer with a carrying amount of &euro;0.7&nbsp;million that served as collateral
	for a bank loan of the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In 2015 this 3D printer was installed in our German service center and transferred to property, plant and equipment with
	a carrying amount of &euro;0.6&nbsp;million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and continued to serve as collateral for such bank loan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	8. voxeljet UK
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Business acquisition
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On October&nbsp;1, 2014, we completed the acquisition of all outstanding shares of Propshop (Model Makers) Limited ("Propshop") which
	became voxeljet UK&nbsp;Ltd. ("voxeljet UK"), a wholly-owned subsidiary of the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, supporting the film and entertainment industry, as well as the
	consumer market for on-demand 3D printing services.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	performed a preliminary purchase price allocation as of December&nbsp;31, 2014 with respect to certain separately identified
	intangible assets. As of March&nbsp;31, 2015, the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	adjusted the purchase price allocation according to the fair values of the intangible assets
	and deferred taxes. Intangible assets were reduced by kEUR 118 with a corresponding increase of the goodwill while
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-19
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	intangible assets acquired in the business combination consisted of order backlog (kEUR 48), customer list (kEUR 622) and digital library (kEUR 464).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	order backlog was amortized until December&nbsp;31, 2014. The customer relations and digital library were to be amortized over a period of three years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	excess of the purchase price over the assets acquired and liabilities assumed was recorded as goodwill of &euro;1.4&nbsp;million. The goodwill resulted from synergies
	which relate to the expanded competencies obtained by
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	in the UK market and the skills of the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
	UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	workforce.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	the fourth quarter of 2014, Propshop's operations contributed revenues of &euro;0.9&nbsp;million and a net loss of &euro;1.1&nbsp;million. The
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	incurred acquisition costs of
	&euro;0.2&nbsp;million, which were recorded as administrative expense.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Restructuring of voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Following a review of the financial performance of
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	and its current market
	environment, Management decided in October 2015 to focus
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK's
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	activities in the future solely on selling high-speed, large-format 3D printers
	and on-demand parts services to industrial and commercial customers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-20
</FONT>
</P>

	Table of Contents

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	8. voxeljet UK (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	a result, the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	entered into an agreement in November 2015 with an investor group that includes the founder of Propshop to sell
	certain assets supporting certain business lines that serve customers in the film and entertainment industry (the DPM business), transfer certain employees and contractual arrangements and settle the
	earnout and employment agreement with the managing director entered into in connection with the acquisition of
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	in exchange for net cash
	consideration of kEUR 365.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	charges from the restructuring of
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	amounted to &euro;2.7&nbsp;million and include a loss from the sale of
	fixed assets, the impairments of certain intangible assets separately identified in the business acquisition and inventories as well as payments for early termination of contracts and the transfer of
	employees. The following table summarizes the amounts relating to the restructuring charges.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_42"></A>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;WIDTH:73%;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
</FONT>
</P>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLEWIDTH,"110%" -->
<!-- USER-SPECIFIED TAGGED TABLE -->
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<TABLE WIDTH="110%" BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0>
<TR>
<!-- TABLE COLUMN WIDTHS SET -->
<TD WIDTH="" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With
	respect to the remaining goodwill arising from the acquisition of
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	of kEUR 1,273, an impairment test was triggered by the
	sale of the DPM business.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	is considered as one cash-generating unit (CGU), which forms part of the Services segment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	recoverable amount of this CGU was based on its value in use, determined by discounting the future expected cash flows to be generated from the continuing use of the CGU. The
	recoverable amount of the CGU of kGBP 2,975 was higher than its carrying amount of kGBP 2,263.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	key assumptions used in the estimation of the recoverable amount are set out below. The key assumptions represent Management's assessment of future trends in the relevant industries
	and have been based on historical data from both external and internal sources. Further, the recoverable amount is particularly sensitive to the achievement of the forecasted revenue.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_43"></A>

</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	discount rate was a pre-tax measure based on the rate of 10-year UK government bonds, adjusted for a risk premium to reflect both the increased risk of investing in equities
	generally and the systematic risk of the specific CGU.
</FONT>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	8. voxeljet UK (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Five
	years of cash flows were included in the discounted cash flow model. A long-term growth rate into perpetuity has been determined with the comparable nominal gross domestic product
	(GDP) rates in the UK.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	forecasted projection on free cash flow was estimated taking into account past experience in the UK and the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company's
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	service centers
	in Germany and the United States.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	estimated recoverable amount of the CGU exceeded its carrying amount by kGBP 712. Management has identified that a reasonably possible change in either the WACC or the revenue
	forecast could result in an impairment. In order to capture the sensitivity in revenues, the estimated revenue for the last year of the plan (2020) was adjusted, while keeping the assumed growth rate
	in terminal value unchanged. The following table shows the amount by which these assumptions would need to change individually for the estimated recoverable amount to be equal to the carrying amount.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_44"></A>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;WIDTH:70%;MARGIN-LEFT:15%;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Due
	to the restructuring of the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet UK
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	business, the intangibles which arose from the business acquisition were impaired (refer to
	Note&nbsp;8). The increase in software occurred as a result of the purchase of software licenses in connection with our new ERP system as well as related capitalized customizing cost. The increase
	regarding licenses was due to the acquisition of a specific license from a third party.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	pledged assets consists of one 3D printer that serves as security for a certain credit line. Amounts added to plant and machinery relating to self-constructed 3D printers are
	considered non-cash transactions, which totaled to kEUR 3,943 and kEUR 392 in the financial years 2015 and 2014, respectively. During 2015, the Group acquired equipment with a carrying amount of kEUR
	39 (2014:&nbsp;kEUR 0) under a finance lease.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	December 2013,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	purchased land, two production halls, and one building under construction in Friedberg, Germany for a total
	purchase price of &euro;10.0&nbsp;million. One of the production halls was previously leased by
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	from the seller; the lease was
	terminated as of December&nbsp;31, 2013. The construction of the administrative building was completed by the end of March 2014. The relocation into the new building occurred in April 2014. In 2013,
	the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	committed to purchase additional land for &euro;0.6&nbsp;million, of which &euro;0.2&nbsp;million was paid in the
	second quarter of 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	total, the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	has entered into sale and leaseback transactions for 17 self-produced 3D&nbsp;printers, which were sold to banks
	and leased back with the intention to be used in the Services segment for the purpose of producing custom-ordered printed products and ultimately to sell them to customers as used
	printers. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	had six active leasing contracts compared to seven in 2014. In 2015, one contract was terminated,
	the 3D printer was repurchased from the lessor and sold to a customer.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	2015 and 2014, there were no new sale and leaseback transactions. In 2013 the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	entered into sale and leaseback transactions for
	four self-produced 3D printers with sales proceeds of kEUR 1,900. In connection with these transactions the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	sold 3D printers with manufacturing
	costs of kEUR 851 in 2013. The gain of kEUR 1,049 from the sale was deferred and is amortized over the respective lease term. Three of the 3D printers are used in the Services segment and one was
	leased to a customer under an operating lease.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Leases
	of 3D printers are non-cash transactions for purposes of the cash flow statement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-24
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	10. Property, plant and equipment (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	connection with the sale of refurbished 3D printers to customers, the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	early terminated one finance lease in 2015 and three in
	2014 and repurchased the applicable 3D printer from the lessor. Four other refurbished printers that had been carried as property, plant and equipment were sold to customers in 2015, while in 2014
	only one other refurbished printer was sold to a customer.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	has a Long-Term Cash Incentive Plan ("LTCIP") that provides for cash awards to non-executive employees. Under the plan, which was
	announced on October&nbsp;2, 2013, the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	may grant individual award units of EUR 5,000 each up to a total maximum amount of 10% of the net
	proceeds received by the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	upon closing of its initial public offering. An initial grant of 684&nbsp;award units was made to participants on
	October&nbsp;2, 2013. The vesting of the awards occurs during three separate performance periods, with 20% of the awards vesting in performance period 1 ended December&nbsp;31, 2013, 40% of the
	awards vesting in performance period 2 ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, and the remaining 40% vesting in performance period 3 ending December&nbsp;31, 2017. Vesting of the awards during performance
	period 1 was subject to a revenue growth target and the successful completion of the initial public offering. Both conditions for performance period 1 were met as of December&nbsp;31, 2013.
	Therefore the awards regarding performance period 2 were paid in 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	September&nbsp;30, 2015, Management granted an additional 131 award units to eligible employees. At grant date the fair value measurement of the liability regarding performance
	period 2 included the assumption, that both the revenue growth as well as the share price target would be achieved. Furthermore, Management expected that the eligible employees would not leave the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	before the settlement of performance period 2. For the assumptions of the fair value measurement related to performance period 3 please refer to
	the section below.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	November 2015, Management decided to reduce the targets for performance periods 2 and 3 of the LTCIP granted awarded in October 2013 which were no longer probable of being achievable
	based on market conditions at the time of the modification. Although the targets for performance period 2 were adjusted, those targets were not achieved. Therefore there will be no payment related to
	the LTCIP for performance period 2.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-25
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	11. Other liabilities and provisions (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Vesting
	of the award during performance period 3 is subject to performance and market conditions, including revenue growth and market capitalization as of December&nbsp;31, 2017. In
	determining the fair value of the liability for the third period of the LTCIP, the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	estimates an 80% probability of achievement for each target,
	revenue growth and market capitalization. This estimation is based on consideration of current market conditions. Moreover, Management expects an employee turnover rate of 5.8% based on past
	experience (2014: 5.0%). The following table shows the development of the accrual regarding the LTCIP.
</FONT>

<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	12. Financial instruments
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fair value is the price that would be received upon sale of an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. The
	fair value hierarchy defines the following levels:
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Level&nbsp;1: Quoted prices of the respective financial asset or financial liability in active markets
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Level&nbsp;2: Other directly observable input parameters which contribute to establishing the fair value based on a valuation model
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Level&nbsp;3: Input parameters not based on observable market data
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Under
	IAS&nbsp;39 there are the following categories:
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	(I)
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	A
	financial asset or financial liability at fair value through profit or loss
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	(II)
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Held-to-maturity
	investments
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	(III)
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Available-for-sale
	financial assets
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	(IV)
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Loans
	and receivables
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	(V)
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Financial
	liabilities measured at amortized cost
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-26
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	financial assets with a carrying amount of &euro;32.0&nbsp;million reported on the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company's
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	statement of financial
	position at December&nbsp;31, 2015 were comprised of investments in three bond funds (&euro;30,661), a note receivable (kEUR 1,075) as well as the remaining unpaid interest from a
	customer loan (kEUR 10), all reported as current financial assets, and restricted cash (kEUR 206) reported as a noncurrent asset.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	of December&nbsp;31, 2014 the financial assets with a carrying amount of &euro;41.4&nbsp;million were comprised of investments in three bond funds (kEUR 39,055), a note
	receivable (kEUR 1,013) and three customer loans (kEUR 1,074), all reported as current financial assets, and restricted cash (kEUR&nbsp;247) reported as a noncurrent asset.
</FONT>
</P>

<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_FQ76001_1_28">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228079Z20-F_HTM_BG76001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<BR>
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	12. Financial instruments (Continued)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	fair value of the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company's
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	investments in the bond funds was determined based on the unit prices quoted by the respective fund
	management company. The funds pursue the goal of daily liquidity and invest in short-term notes. The funds are open-ended; the units can be redeemed to the fund on a daily basis. Unit prices updated
	by the fund management company on a daily basis represent a quoted price in an active market.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	fair value of the note receivable due January 2016 was based on the secondary market price quoted by a broker.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	fair value of customer loans at December&nbsp;31, 2014 was determined using a discounted cash flow model based on observable inputs from the relevant forward interest rate yield
	curve plus an appropriate risk premium.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	fair value of long-term debt was determined using discounted cash flow models based on the relevant forward interest rate yield curves. The fair value of finance lease obligations
	was determined using discounted cash flow models based on market interest rates available to the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	for similar transactions at the relevant date.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Due
	to the short maturity and the current low level of interest rates, the carrying amount of credit lines and bank overdrafts and customer loan at December&nbsp;31, 2015 approximate
	fair value.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	13. Cost of sales
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cost of sales includes personnel expenses, cost of material, purchased services, cost for finished goods and allocated indirect costs related to production.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	2015 other expenses consisted of rental expenses (kEUR 736), license fees (kEUR 440), travel expenses (kEUR 394) and tooling kits (kEUR 211). In 2014 and 2013, other expenses
	primarily consisted of rental expenses for manufacturing space.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	14. Other operating income and expense
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other operating income includes primarily government grants received for ongoing research and development projects, the recognition of the gain on sale and leaseback transactions upon
	release from deferred income and gains from foreign exchange transactions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-28
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	15. Financial result
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the periods 2015, 2014 and 2013, the financial result was mainly driven by interest expense on finance leases, bank overdrafts and drawings under credit lines and long-term debt.
</FONT>
</P>

	2015, 2014 and 2013, deferred tax (expense) benefit resulted from changes in deferred tax assets and liabilities on temporary differences.

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At
	December&nbsp;31, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	had gross loss carry-forwards for corporation tax and trade tax losses of kEUR 10,335 and kEUR
	10,090, respectively, for which no deferred taxes have been recognized. These tax losses can be carried forward without restriction for future offset against taxable profits. In addition, there are
	foreign tax loss carry-forwards of kEUR 9,309.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	addition, a valuation allowance of kEUR 132 on net deferred tax assets related to sale and leaseback transactions was recorded in 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-31
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet&nbsp;AG
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	offers to its employees a defined contribution plan called "MetallRente". The contributions paid by the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	amounted to kEUR 41, kEUR 30 and kEUR
	23 for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively. The employer's contribution
	into the mandatory German state plan amounted to kEUR 511, kEUR 389 and kEUR 266 for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and 2013, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-0PT;" -->
	18. Segment reporting
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	operates in two reportable segments&#151;Systems and Services&#151;which reflect the internal organizational and
	management structure according to the distinct nature of the two businesses. The Systems business derives its revenues from the manufacture and sale of 3D printers, from the sale of consumables as
	well as lease and maintenance agreements with customers, while the Services business provides custom-ordered printed product to customers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	measurement principles used by
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	in preparing this segment reporting are also the basis for segment performance assessment. The
	Chief Executive Officer of
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	voxeljet
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	acts as a chief operating
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	F-32
</FONT>
</P>

	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS (Continued)
</B>

<FONT SIZE=2>

	18. Segment reporting (Continued)
</B>

</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	decision
	maker. As a performance indicator, the chief operating decision maker mainly monitors the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company's
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	revenues and gross profit.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	following table summarizes segment reporting for each of the reporting periods ended December&nbsp;31. As Management's controlling instruments are mainly revenue-based, the
	reporting information does not include a detailed breakdown of all assets and liabilities by category. The sum of the amounts for the two segments equals the total for the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	for each of the years
	presented.

<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	SEGMENT REPORTING
</B>
</FONT>

<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;WIDTH:62%;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLEWIDTH,"130%" -->
<!-- USER-SPECIFIED TAGGED TABLE -->
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<TABLE WIDTH="130%" BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0>

</TD>

<FONT SIZE=2>

	2015 and 2014 no customer represented 10% or more of total revenue. In 2013, the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	had one customer who represented 13% of total
	revenues.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	2014, on two occasions the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	provided loans to customers to cover a portion of the purchase price of a 3D printer. The
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Company
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	recognized revenue
	from the sale of these 3D printers upon acceptance by the customer at the fair value of the consideration received which was
	comprised of cash and the loan.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE=2>
<A NAME="A2228079Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_FS76001_1_35">
</A>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_BASECOLOR,"BLACK" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DEFAULTFONT,"FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLESHADECOLOR,"#CCEEFF" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_STABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:DOUBLE #000000 2.25PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_SCRTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;" -->
